  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Mobilizing knowledge to support community resilience to climate change</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Cabo Verde has an arid and semi-arid, hot and dry climate with scarce rainfall on average. Climate change, irregular and low rainfalls threatens the sustainable management of the mostly marine and mountain eco-systems, livelihoods and food supply. In 2018, Cape Verde faced the worst drought since 1977 that affected up to 70,000 people. A third of the population living in rural areas-belong to a family that is engaged in agricultural activities and is therefore directly exposed to droughts. We propose two activities: development of an accurate and rapidly implementable flood and drought (F&amp;D) monitoring critical for assessing and anticipating the impacts and consequences on agriculture, ecosystems and the economy and an enhanced Sandwatch programme that takes into account Citizen Science.</narrative>
  </description>
